const a = [
  {"id":15331,"text":"A 32-year-old plumber developed pneumonia and was in the hospital for a week. The sputum was sent for culture and sensitivity. Laboratory reports showed Gram-positive cocci arranged in clusters. What is the causative organism?","explanation":"Pneumonia in a patient who has been hospitalized for a week suggests a nosocomial infection, which can include ***Staphylococcus aureus*** as a potential pathogen. It typically appears as Gram-positive cocci arranged in clusters when observed under a microscope.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n*Neisseria meningitidis* is a Gram-negative bacterium primarily associated with meningitis and sepsis. It is not typically a cause of pneumonia.\r\n\r\n*Legionella pneumophila* is a Gram-negative coccobacillus.\r\n\r\n*Streptococcus pneumoniae* typically appears as Gram-positive cocci in pairs (diplococci), not in clusters.\r\n\r\n*Escherichia* coli is a Gram-negative a gram-negative bacillus.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 104, 106.","responses":[{"text":"Neisseria meningitidis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Escherichia coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Legionella pneumophila","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15332,"text":"A 42-year-old woman was diagnosed with metastatic cervical cancer. Cervical cancers are mostly associated with human papillomavirus infections, which are now preventable with the help of vaccines. This vaccine is made up of which of the following?","explanation":"Human papillomavirus (HPV) vaccines are composed of virus-like particles (VLPs) that are generated using **recombinant** DNA technology. These VLPs are made from the structural **proteins** of HPV, specifically the L1 capsid protein. They mimic the outer shell of the virus without containing viral DNA, making them non-infectious.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHPV vaccines are composed of recombinant proteins without live or killed viruses.\r\n\r\nWhile HPV vaccines stimulate the production of antibodies in the recipient's body, the vaccines themselves are not made up of antibodies.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 272.","responses":[{"text":"Live attenuated viruses","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A mix of live and killed vaccines","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Killed viruses","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Recombinant protein","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15333,"text":"A 45-year-old patient presented to the clinic with a postoperative surgical site infection after an emergency laparotomy. The sample was pus collected in a sterile syringe and sent to the laboratory for routine culture and sensitivity. Gram-stain revealed Gram-positive cocci in clusters with numerous pus cells. After 24 hours, beta-hemolytic colonies grew on the sheep blood agar plate, which was coagulase and catalase positive. What is the most likely causative agent?","explanation":"***Staphylococcus aureus*** is a Gram-positive coccus that is a leading cause of postoperative wound infections. It forms beta-hemolytic colonies on sheep blood agar, and is coagulase and catalase positive.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n*Streptococcus pyogenes* is not coagulase positive.\r\n\r\n*Staphylococcus saprophyticus* is associated with urinary tract infections.\r\n\r\n*Staphylococcus epidermidis* is a coagulase-negative staphylococcus that is commonly found on the skin and mucous membranes. While it can be associated with healthcare-associated infections, it is less likely to cause postoperative surgical site infections compared to *Staphylococcus aureus*.\r\n\r\n*Streptococcus pneumoniae* is a leading cause of respiratory infections such as pneumonia.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 106-108.","responses":[{"text":"Streptococcus pyogenes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus epidermidis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus saprophyticus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15334,"text":"A 15-year-old girl was brought to the emergency unit by her mother with complaints of sudden fever, headache, and stiff neck. Other symptoms were nausea, vomiting, increased sensitivity to light, and confusion. Cerebrospinal fluid was sent to the laboratory for routine culture and a detailed report. Microscopic examination showed diplococci organisms. Growth revealed grey colonies, which were catalase negative. Which of the following bacteria is most probably causing infection?","explanation":"Sudden fever, headache, stiff neck, nausea, vomiting, increased sensitivity to light (photophobia), and confusion are highly suggestive of acute bacterial meningitis. The description of grey colonies on culture, along with being **catalase-negative**, is consistent with the characteristics of ***Neisseria meningitidis***; a **Gram-negative diplococcus** bacterium known to cause meningitis. It is a leading cause of bacterial meningitis in adolescents and young adults.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nEnterococci are Gram-positive bacteria.\r\n\r\nStreptococcus viridians are also Gram-positive bacteria.\r\n\r\n*Streptococcus pyogenes* is more commonly associated with conditions such as strep throat and skin infections.\r\n\r\n*Neisseria gonorrhoeae* is a sexually transmitted bacterium that can cause gonorrhea but is not typically associated with acute bacterial meningitis.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 127.","responses":[{"text":"Neisseria gonorrhoeae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus viridians","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria meningitidis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterococcus species","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pyogenes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15336,"text":"Several vaccines are prepared using different bacterial components. Sometimes after vaccinating the population, vaccine-escape variants emerge. The most often component used in the development of bacterial vaccines is which of the following?","explanation":"**Capsular polysaccharide vaccines** are commonly used to immunize against bacterial pathogens that possess capsules, such as *Streptococcus pneumoniae*, *Haemophilus influenzae* type b (Hib), and *Neisseria meningitidis*.\r\n\r\nBacterial capsules are protective outer layers made up of polysaccharides or proteins that surround the bacterial cell wall. They play a critical role in bacterial virulence and immune evasion. Many bacterial vaccines target the capsule as it contains antigens that can stimulate the production of antibodies in the host's immune system. These antibodies can then recognize and neutralize bacteria with the same capsule composition.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 93.","responses":[{"text":"Ribosome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cell wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Capsule","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cell membrane","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15346,"text":"Myc gene is implicated in which disorder?","explanation":"**Burkitt lymphoma** is characterized by a translocation between the Myc gene on chromosome 8 and an immunoglobulin gene on chromosome 14 (t(8;14) translocation). This translocation leads to the overexpression of the **Myc oncogene**.\r\n\r\nThe Myc gene encodes a transcription factor that regulates cell growth and proliferation. When overexpressed as a result of the translocation, it contributes to the uncontrolled growth of lymphocytes, leading to the development of Burkitt lymphoma.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nColon cancer is primarily associated with genetic mutations such as adenomatous polyposis coli (APC), Kirsten rat sarcoma viral oncogene homolog (KRAS), and (tumor protein 53 (TP53).\r\n\r\nChronic myeloid leukemia (CML) is characterized by the Philadelphia chromosome, which results from a translocation between chromosomes 9 and 22.\r\n\r\nFollicular lymphoma is associated with a translocation involving the BCL2 gene on chromosome 18.\r\n\r\nFibroblasts are cells found in connective tissues and can give rise to fibrosarcoma, a malignant tumor of fibrous tissue. The molecular alterations involved in fibrosarcoma development may vary, but the Myc gene is not a common driver in this type of cancer.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 316.","responses":[{"text":"Chronic myeloid leukemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neoplasia of fibroblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Burkitt lymphoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicular lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colon cancer","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15347,"text":"A 32-year-old patient develops fever and myalgia. The physician orders a complete blood count (CBC). In case of a viral illness, the CBC will show an increase in which of the following?","explanation":"**Viral infections** typically lead to an immune response characterized by an increase in lymphocytes in the bloodstream. These cells work together to combat the virus. This increase is known as **lymphocytosis**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nBasophils are a type of white blood cell (WBC) that plays a role in allergic reactions and parasitic infections.\r\n\r\nPlasma cells are specialized B lymphocytes (B cells) that produce antibodies as part of the immune response. An increase in plasma cells is not a typical feature of viral illnesses but can occur in certain chronic infections or autoimmune diseases.\r\n\r\nAn increase in neutrophils, known as neutrophilia, is more commonly associated with bacterial infections.\r\n\r\nMast cells are involved in allergic reactions and the release of histamine.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 588.","responses":[{"text":"Plasma cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mast cell","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15349,"text":"A young boy suffered from multiple infections. Family history was suggestive of antibody deficiency. His complete blood picture showed normal levels of T and B lymphocytes, however, serum immunoglobulin levels were markedly low. Which antibodies can activate the complement system?","explanation":"**IgG** and **IgM** antibodies are capable of activating the classical complement pathway. When these antibodies bind to antigens on the surface of pathogens, they can initiate the classical pathway, leading to the **activation of complement proteins** and subsequent immune responses.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nIgA is primarily involved in mucosal immunity.\r\n\r\nIgE is primarily associated with allergic responses and defense against parasites.\r\n\r\nIgD is mainly found on the surface of B cells and has a role in antigen recognition.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 196, 203.","responses":[{"text":"IgE and IgG","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA and IgM","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgG and IgM","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IgG and IgD","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgD and IgA","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15351,"text":"25-year-old sexually active woman complaint of greenish-yellow vaginal discharge. Culture shows Gram-negative diplococci. What is the causative agent?","explanation":"***Neisseria gonorrhoeae*** is a Gram-negative diplococcus bacterium that commonly causes gonorrhea, a sexually transmitted infection (STI). One of the hallmark clinical presentations of gonorrhea in women is a **greenish-yellow vaginal discharge**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n*Legionella pneumophila* is a bacterium responsible for Legionnaires disease, a severe form of pneumonia.\r\n\r\n*Pseudomonas aeruginosa* is a bacterium known for causing various infections, including respiratory and skin infections.\r\n\r\n*Staphylococcus aureus* is a Gram-positive bacterium often associated with skin and soft tissue infections, as well as other types of infections.\r\n\r\n*Streptococcus pneumoniae* is a Gram-positive bacterium responsible for causing pneumonia and other respiratory tract infections.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 127-128.","responses":[{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria gonorrhoeae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudomonas aeruginosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Legionella pneumophilia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15352,"text":"Which branch of forensics deals with performing autopsies and determining the cause of death?","explanation":"**Forensic pathology** is the branch of forensics that deals with performing **autopsies** and determining the cause of death. This field focuses on examining deceased individuals to establish the circumstances and reasons behind their demise, including whether it was due to natural causes, accidents, suicides, homicides, or other factors. Forensic pathologists play a crucial role in the criminal justice system by providing critical information in cases involving suspicious or unexplained deaths.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nForensic computer science deals with the analysis of digital evidence, such as computer data and electronic devices, in the context of criminal investigations.\r\n\r\nWhile \"forensic sciences\" is a broad term encompassing various forensic disciplines, it does not specifically address the task of performing autopsies and determining the cause of death. Forensic sciences include multiple subfields, such as forensic biology, chemistry, and anthropology, each with its own focus.\r\n\r\nForensic toxicology primarily involves the analysis of body fluids and tissues for the presence of drugs, alcohol, or poisons. While it can be related to determining the cause of death in some cases, it does not encompass the complete scope of forensic pathology, which involves a comprehensive examination of deceased individuals.\r\n\r\nForensic serology is concerned with the identification and analysis of bodily fluids (e.g., blood, semen, saliva) found at crime scenes. It is not directly involved in performing autopsies or determining the cause of death.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 98.","responses":[{"text":"Forensic serology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Forensic computer science","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Forensic toxicology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Forensic pathology","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Forensic sciences","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15353,"text":"What is the main aim to perform an autopsy?","explanation":"An **autopsy** is a post-mortem examination of a deceased person's body, typically performed by a forensic pathologist. Its primary purpose is to determine the **cause of death**. During an autopsy, the pathologist carefully examines the body, internal organs, tissues, and conducts various tests to investigate the circumstances surrounding the person's death. Identifying the cause of death is essential for legal, medical, and investigative purposes.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAn autopsy is performed on the bodies of individuals who have already been officially declared deceased, after confirming that there are no signs of life.\r\n\r\nDetecting poisoning can be a part of the autopsy process, especially if it is suspected. However, the primary aim remains identifying the cause of death, which may include poisoning as a possible cause.\r\n\r\nIdentifying injuries or trauma is indeed a part of the autopsy examination. Still, the main objective is to determine the cause of death, which may or may not be related to injuries.\r\n\r\nSimilar to poisoning, the presence of drug overdose can be investigated during an autopsy, but the primary purpose is to identify the actual cause of death.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 98.","responses":[{"text":"To exclude poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To exclude drug overdose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To look for any possible injuries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To identify the cause of death","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"To look for signs of life","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15354,"text":"What is the demerit of arsenic as an ideal homicidal poison?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 492.","responses":[{"text":"It is rapid in action","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It retards putrefaction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It has a characteristic taste","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is toxic in large doses","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is not easily avaliable","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15355,"text":"An ideal homicidal poison should not be which of the following?","explanation":"In an ideal homicidal poison, several characteristics are considered desirable to effectively carry out a poisoning without arousing suspicion. The poison should be easily mixed with food or drink, ensuring that the victim consumes it without suspicion. An ideal homicidal poison should be tasteless and odorless to prevent the victim from detecting any unusual or unpleasant flavors or smells, which could lead to suspicion.\r\n\r\nA rapid-acting poison is preferred to cause quick and lethal effects, minimizing the chances of the victim seeking medical attention or intervention.\r\n\r\nAn ideal homicidal poison should be easy to obtain without arousing suspicion.\r\n\r\nTo avoid suspicion, the symptoms produced by the poison should resemble those of a natural disease, making it less likely for the death to be attributed to foul play.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 468.","responses":[{"text":"Easily available","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Should be palatable","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Symptoms should resemble natural disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Should be rapid in action","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tasteless and odorless","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15356,"text":"Gastric lavage is contraindicated in which of the following poisoning?","explanation":"Corrosive substances, such as strong acids or bases, can cause severe damage to the digestive tract, including the esophagus, stomach, and intestines. Attempting **gastric lavage** in cases of **corrosive poisoning** can further exacerbate the damage by introducing more trauma to the already affected tissues. Therefore, it is **contraindicated**, and other methods of treatment should be pursued, such as immediate medical intervention and supportive care.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nGastric lavage may be considered for certain cases of arsenic poisoning, especially if it is performed promptly after ingestion.\r\n\r\nDhatura, or thorn apple, contains toxic alkaloids. Gastric lavage may be considered if the ingestion is recent and the patient is stable.\r\n\r\nSnake venom poisoning usually results from a bite, not ingestion, thus gastric lavage would not be applicable or beneficial in these cases. However, it is not a contraindication for gastric lavage.\r\n\r\nOrganophosphorus poisoning, typically from pesticides, is not a universal contraindication for gastric lavage. The decision to use gastric lavage should be made based on the individual patient's condition and risk of complications like aspiration.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 474.","responses":[{"text":"Dhatora","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corrosive","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Snake","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Organophosphorus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arsenic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15357,"text":"If water is used for gastric lavage, preferably it should be which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 491.","responses":[{"text":"Luke warm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sterilize","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cold","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Warm","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15358,"text":"The antidotes which act by forming new less toxic compounds with poison are termed as which of the following?","explanation":"**Chemical antidotes** work by directly interacting with the poison to form a new compound that is less harmful than the original toxin. This transformation reduces the toxicity of the poison and facilitates its excretion from the body.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nPhysiological antidotes counteract the poison by producing an opposite physiological effect but do not necessarily interact chemically with the poison.\r\n\r\nPhysical antidotes prevent the absorption of the poison from the gastrointestinal tract, typically by adsorption or binding, but do not chemically react with the poison to form a new compound.\r\n\r\nChelating agents are a specific type of chemical antidote used particularly for heavy metal poisonings. They bind to the metal ions, forming stable complexes that are then excreted from the body. While they are a subset of chemical antidotes, they represent a specific mechanism of action.\r\n\r\nUniversal antidotes are a concept where a single antidote can counteract a wide range of poisons. However, in practice, there is no true \"universal\" antidote that is effective against all or most poisons.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Foundation-II module, Forensic Medicine slides, Topic: Administration of antidotes.","responses":[{"text":"Chelating agents","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemical antidotes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Universal antidotes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Physiological antidotes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Physical antidotes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15359,"text":"What is the treatment of choice for lead poisoning?","explanation":"**Lead poisoning** occurs when there is an accumulation of lead in the body, which can have serious health consequences, particularly in children. **Ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid** (EDTA) is a chelating agent, which means it forms stable complexes with lead ions in the body. These complexes are then excreted from the body, reducing the lead burden.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nBritish Anti-Lewisite (BAL) also known as dimercaprol, is an antidote for arsenic.\r\n\r\nPenicillamine is used to treat Wilson disease (copper overload).\r\n\r\nActivated charcoal is used to absorb toxins in cases of acute poisoning but is not specific to lead poisoning and does not address the underlying lead accumulation.\r\n\r\nDeferoxamine is used for iron chelation in cases of iron overload, such as in hemochromatosis.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides: Foundation-II module, Forensic Medicine slides, Topic: Important Chelating Agents.","responses":[{"text":"Ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid (EDTA)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Deferoxamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penicillamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"British Anti-Lewisite (BAL)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activated charcoal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15360,"text":"What is the ideal position of patient while performing gastric lavage?","explanation":"In the **left lateral position**, the stomach is oriented in such a way that reduces the risk of aspiration, which is a significant concern during **gastric lavage**. This position helps ensure that the liquid contents are more likely to flow towards the pylorus and into the small intestine, rather than regurgitating back into the esophagus and potentially into the respiratory tract.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nProne position is not used for gastric lavage due to the high risk of aspiration and difficulty in performing the procedure in this position.\r\n\r\nFowler position, while useful in certain medical situations to aid in breathing, is not ideal for gastric lavage as it increases the risk of aspiration.\r\n\r\nRight lateral position is less favorable than the left lateral position for gastric lavage, as it can increase the risk of regurgitation and aspiration.\r\n\r\nSupine position is generally avoided because it poses the highest risk for aspiration, which can lead to serious complications such as aspiration pneumonia.","reference":"(1) Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 516. \r\n\r\n(2) Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 473.","responses":[{"text":"Right lateral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left lateral","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fowler's position","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15363,"text":"What does the sympathetic stimulation of the iris cause?","explanation":"When the **sympathetic** nervous system is activated, it prepares the body for action. This includes **dilating** the **pupils** to allow more light to enter the eye, improving vision for potential threats, or in situations where heightened awareness is needed.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAstigmatism is a refractive error in the eye due to an irregularly shaped cornea or lens.\r\n\r\nPupillary constriction is typically controlled by the parasympathetic nervous system. It occurs in response to bright light or during near-vision tasks.\r\n\r\nDiplopia is double vision, which can occur due to various factors, including problems with eye alignment or neurological issues.\r\n\r\nThe vitreous is a gel-like substance that fills the interior of the eye. Sympathetic stimulation of the iris does not lead to vitreous secretion. The vitreous is a stable, non-secretory component of the eye.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 40.","responses":[{"text":"Viterous secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pupillary constriction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Astigmatism (vision blurry or distorted)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diplopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pupillary dilation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15364,"text":"In the division of the autonomic system, from where do parasympathetic fibers originate?","explanation":"**Parasympathetic fibers** originate from **cranial nerves** III (oculomotor), VII (facial), IX (glossopharyngeal), and X (vagus). These nerves control various functions in the head and neck region.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, parasympathetic fibers also originate from the **sacral region** of the spinal cord, specifically from spinal segments S2 to S4. These fibers innervate pelvic organs and lower abdominal structures.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 40.","responses":[{"text":"The thoraco-lumbar spinal region","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The cervico-lumbar region","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The cranio-lumbar region","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The cervico-thoracic region","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The cranio-sacral regions","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15365,"text":"Which of the following statements is incorrect regarding pilocarpine?","explanation":"**Pilocarpine** primarily acts on **muscarinic** receptors, not nicotinic receptors. Muscarinic receptors are found in the effector organs of the parasympathetic nervous system and are responsible for the effects of acetylcholine.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nPilocarpine is a cholinergic drug that stimulates the parasympathetic nervous system. It increases secretions such as saliva, sweat, and tears.\r\n\r\nPilocarpine indeed has a relatively short duration of action, which is approximately 1 hour.\r\n\r\nPilocarpine is indeed used to lower intraocular pressure in conditions like glaucoma and is considered a drug of choice for this purpose.\r\n\r\n Pilocarpine is indeed an alkaloid, which is a naturally occurring organic compound.","reference":"(1) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 51, 54.\r\n\r\n(2) Dow Lecture slides: Foundation-II module, Pharmacology slides, Topic: Parasympathetic drugs, Subtopic: Cholinergic agonists.","responses":[{"text":"Increases body secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is an alkaloid in nature","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duration of action is about 1 hour","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acts on nicotonic receptors","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Drug of choice for emergency lowering intraocular pressure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15366,"text":"Which statement is not correct about bethanechol?","explanation":"**Bethanechol** is **resistant** to degradation by **acetylcholinesterase**, which is an enzyme responsible for breaking down acetylcholine. This resistance to degradation is one of the characteristics that make bethanechol suitable for therapeutic use.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nBethanechol is a muscarinic receptor agonist and is more specific for muscarinic receptors found in smooth muscle, including those in the bladder and gastrointestinal tract, rather than nicotinic receptors which are primarily found at neuromuscular junctions.\r\n\r\nBethanechol has a relatively short duration of action, lasting about 1 hour, which makes it suitable for conditions where short-term stimulation of muscarinic receptors is desired.\r\n\r\nBethanechol is indeed structurally composed of carbamate and methylated choline, which are essential components of its chemical structure.\r\n\r\nBethanechol is used to treat atony (lack of muscle tone) of the bladder, as it stimulates muscarinic receptors in the bladder smooth muscle, promoting bladder contraction and aiding in the expulsion of urine.","reference":"(1) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 53. \r\n\r\n(2) Dow Lecture slides: Foundation-II Module, Pharmacology Slides, Topic: Parasympathetic drugs, Subtopic: Cholinergic agonists.","responses":[{"text":"Used for atony of bladder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Structurally consists of carbamate and methylated choline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"More specific for muscarinic receptors than nicotinic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duration of action is about 1 hour","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rapidly degraded by acetylcholinesterase enzyme","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15407,"text":"Which of the following does forensic medicine not deal with?","explanation":"Forensic medicine primarily deals with the investigation of various aspects related to law and medicine, particularly in cases involving injuries, crimes, and death.\r\n\r\nIt can involve the examination and documentation of physical abuse or injuries resulting from abuse, which may have legal implications.\r\n\r\nForensic medicine is heavily involved in determining the cause and manner of death, and investigating homicides, suicides, accidents, and natural deaths.\r\n\r\nMedical malpractice involves professional negligence by healthcare providers. It falls under medical ethics and legal proceedings.\r\n\r\nForensic medicine plays a significant role in examining victims of sexual assault, collecting evidence, and providing expert testimony in court cases related to sexual assault.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Foundation-2 module, Subject: Forensic Medicine, Topic: Law Related to Medical Man, Sub-topic: Scope of Forensic Medicine.","responses":[{"text":"Sexual assault","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abuse","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Life and death","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mechanics","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Medical malpractice","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15408,"text":"A 45-year-old female developed a fever with burning micturition. She was diagnosed with having urinary tract infection. The growth on the blood agar showed swarming organisms. Other chemical tests were performed. Gram-negative, non-spore-forming, oxidase-negative, non-lactose fermenting, H₂S-producing rod-shaped bacteria were isolated. Infection in the urinary tract may occur with indwelling catheters. Which organism is isolated in this patient?","explanation":"***Proteus mirabilis*** is a Gram-negative bacterium that does not form spores and is **oxidase-negative**. Furthermore, *P. mirabilis* is known as a **non-lactose fermenter** and is capable of producing **hydrogen sulfide** (H₂S), which can be detected in specific biochemical tests. It grows on blood agar and is a common causative agent of urinary tract infections, particularly in cases involving **indwelling catheters**, due to its propensity to ascend the urinary tract and form stones.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n*Salmonella typhi* is associated with typhoid fever, which typically presents with systemic symptoms such as high fever, rather than urinary tract infections.\r\n\r\n*Neisseria* species are usually associated with different infections, such as *N. gonorrhoeae* causing gonorrhea or *N. meningitidis* causing meningitis. They are not typically implicated in urinary tract infections.\r\n\r\n*Legionella* is associated with Legionnaires' disease, a respiratory illness.\r\n\r\nWhile *Escherichia coli* (E. coli) can cause urinary tract infections, it is typically lactose fermenting.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 145-146, 157-158.","responses":[{"text":"Legionella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Escherichia coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proteus mirabilis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Salmonella typhi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15448,"text":"A 42-year-old patient was suspected of having tuberculosis. Microscopy showed acid-fast bacilli. What will be the medium of choice for the culture of these bacteria?","explanation":"**Löwenstein-Jensen agar** is a selective medium specifically designed for the isolation and growth of **acid-fast bacilli** such as *Mycobacterium tuberculosis*. It contains inhibitors that suppress the growth of other bacteria while allowing mycobacteria to grow.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMacConkey agar is used for the isolation of Gram-negative enteric bacteria.\r\n\r\nEosin-methylene blue (EMB) agar is also used for the isolation of Gram-negative bacteria, particularly coliforms.\r\n\r\nBlood agar is used for the general cultivation of a wide range of bacteria, including those that may not be acid-fast. It does not have the selectivity needed for isolating mycobacteria.\r\n\r\nChocolate agar is primarily used for the cultivation of fastidious organisms like *Haemophilus influenzae* and *Neisseria* species, but it is not selective for mycobacteria.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 60.","responses":[{"text":"Eosin-methylene blue (EMB) agar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood agar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Löwenstein-Jensen agar","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"MacConkey agar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chocolate agar","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15449,"text":"Which of the following diseases is inherited in an X-linked recessive fashion?","explanation":"In **X-linked recessive inheritance**, the faulty gene responsible for the disease is located on the X chromosome. Males have one X and one Y chromosome, while females have two X chromosomes. If a male inherits a defective X chromosome carrying the DMD gene, he will develop **Duchenne muscular dystrophy** because there is no second healthy X chromosome to compensate.\r\n\r\nFemales with one healthy X chromosome and one affected X chromosome are carriers but are typically not affected.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMarfan syndrome and Huntington disease are autosomal dominant disorders.\r\n\r\nThalassemia can be inherited in various ways, including autosomal recessive, but it is not exclusively X-linked recessive.\r\n\r\nSickle cell disease is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 146.","responses":[{"text":"Duchenne muscular dystrophy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Huntington disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thalassemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Marfan syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cell disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15450,"text":"Tumor-associated antigens are antigens present on the surface of the tumor cells. What is true for these antigens?","explanation":"**Tumor-associated antigens** are typically derived from normal cellular components but may be altered in tumor cells. These altered antigens can be recognized by the immune system as foreign or \"**non-self**.\" This recognition can trigger an immune response against the tumor.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTumor-associated antigens do not mimic normal body antigens; they may be derived from normal antigens but are altered in tumor cells.\r\n\r\nTumor-associated antigens are not undetectable; they can be recognized by the immune system.\r\n\r\nTumor-associated antigens can develop in various types of tumors, not only those induced by viruses.\r\n\r\nWhile some tumor-associated antigens can be specific to certain tumors, others may be shared among different types of tumors. The specificity can vary.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 309-310.","responses":[{"text":"Are always specific for specific tumors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Are immunologically undetectable","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Only develop in tumors induced by viruses","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mimics antigens of the body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Can be recognized as non-self antigens","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15451,"text":"Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) causes a reduction of T cell count to a level where the patient becomes severely deficient. HIV preferentially attacks which of the following?","explanation":"**HIV** is a retrovirus that specifically infects and replicates within helper T cells. It attaches to the CD4 receptor on the surface of these cells and enters them, ultimately leading to the destruction of **helper T cells**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nBasophils, B cells, cytotoxic T cells, and macrophages types of white blood cells, but they are not the main targets of HIV.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 366.","responses":[{"text":"Helper T cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytotoxic T cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15452,"text":"HLA-DR2 is a risk factor for which of the following?","explanation":"The Human Leukocyte Antigen (HLA) system plays a crucial role in the immune system by helping the body recognize self-antigens from non-self. Studies have shown that individuals carrying the **HLA-DR2 allele** are at a higher risk of developing **multiple sclerosis** (MS).\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHLA-DR3 and HLA-DR4 are more commonly associated with type I diabetes.\r\n\r\nMyasthenia gravis is primarily associated with antibodies against the acetylcholine receptor or muscle-specific tyrosine kinase. HLA-DR2 is not a primary risk factor for this condition.\r\n\r\nRheumatoid arthritis is associated with HLA-DR4 ) and HLA-DR1.\r\n\r\nAnkylosing spondylitis is strongly associated with HLA-B27.","reference":"Hla-dr2 - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed March 22, 2023. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/neuroscience/hla-dr2","responses":[{"text":"Myasthenia gravis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multiple sclerosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ankylosing spondylitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin-dependent (type I) diabetes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rheumatoid arthritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15453,"text":"A number of diseases are detected through antigen-antibody reactions. Which test utilizes this mechanism?","explanation":"**Enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay** (ELISA) relies on the specific binding of antigens to antibodies. It is used to detect the presence of specific antibodies or antigens in a given sample.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nProbe analysis can refer to various techniques for analyzing DNA, RNA, or proteins.\r\n\r\nPolymerase chain reaction (PCR) is a method for amplifying DNA, not for detecting diseases through antigen-antibody reactions. It is used to replicate and amplify specific DNA sequences.\r\n\r\nCulture and sensitivity involves growing microorganisms from a sample and testing their susceptibility to antibiotics.\r\n\r\nGenome sequencing involves determining the complete DNA sequence of an organism. While it can be used to identify genetic factors related to diseases, it is not primarily based on antigen-antibody reactions.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 60, 63.","responses":[{"text":"Enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Culture and sensitivity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polymerase chain reaction (PCR)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Genome sequencing","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Probe analysis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15454,"text":"A toxoid is an inactivated toxin that has lost its ability to cause disease but has retained its immunogenicity. The vaccines against which of these bacterial infections contains toxoid as an antigen?","explanation":"**Diphtheria** and **tetanus** vaccines are examples of **toxoid vaccines**. They contain inactivated toxins (toxoids) produced by *Corynebacterium diphtheriae* and *Clostridium tetani*, respectively. These toxoids have lost their ability to cause disease but can still stimulate a strong immune response when introduced into the body.\r\n\r\nThe immune response generated by these toxoid vaccines protects against the diseases caused by the active toxins produced by these bacteria.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nVaccines against *Neisseria meningitidis* typically contain components like polysaccharides or protein subunits from the bacteria's outer membrane.\r\n\r\nThe vaccine for *Mycobacterium tuberculosis*, known as the Bacille Calmette-Guérin (BCG) vaccine, uses an inactivated pathogen rather than a toxoid. \r\n\r\nVaccines against *Streptococcus pneumoniae*, such as pneumococcal vaccines, typically use capsular polysaccharides from various pneumococcal strains as antigens. \r\n\r\nVaccines against *Haemophilus influenzae*, particularly *Haemophilus influenzae* type b (Hib) vaccines, use components like capsular polysaccharides or protein conjugates.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 93.","responses":[{"text":"Mycobacterium tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diphtheria and tetanus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haemophilus influenza","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria meningitidis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16115,"text":"Regarding the oncogene of DNA tumor viruses, which of the following is most accurate?","explanation":"**DNA tumor viruses**, such as human papillomaviruses (HPVs), Epstein-Barr virus (EBV), and adenoviruses, typically contribute to oncogenesis by producing **viral proteins** that interact with key **tumor suppressor proteins** in the host cell. For example, proteins like HPV's E6 and E7 can bind to and inactivate tumor suppressor proteins like p53 and Rb (retinoblastoma protein), respectively. By disrupting the normal function of these tumor suppressor proteins, the virus can induce uncontrolled cell proliferation, leading to cancer.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile phosphorylation of p53 is a significant regulatory mechanism in cell cycle control, this is not typically the primary function of viral oncogenes.\r\n\r\nWhile some viruses may induce cellular factors that promote DNA synthesis, the key mechanism of oncogenesis for these viruses is the direct interaction with tumor suppressor proteins.\r\n\r\nDNA tumor viruses do not typically encode \"muscular growth factors,\" and their role in cancer is not directly related to muscle or G-phase DNA synthesis.\r\n\r\nWhile interaction with proto-oncogenes is a feature of some oncogenic processes, DNA tumor viruses primarily exert their effects through interaction with tumor suppressor genes.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2020: 363.","responses":[{"text":"They interact with cellular proto-oncogenes and activates them","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They encode cellular growth factors that activates S-phase DNA synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They encode muscular growth factors that activates G-phase DNA synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They encode protein kinase that phosphorylates p53 protein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They encode proteins that bind to the proteins coded by tumor suppressor genes","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16116,"text":"While reading the antimicrobial susceptibility results, the technologist noticed gaps in the growth of bacteria. Viruses that infect and kill the bacteria resemble the lunar lander and are composed of polyhedral heads, helical bodies, and legs that attach to the cell membrane so that they can transfer their genetic material. Bacteriophage belongs to which of the following classes of virus?","explanation":"**Bacteriophages**, which are viruses that infect and kill bacteria, belong to the **complex** class of viruses. They have a complex structure with polyhedral heads, helical bodies, and appendages (legs or tails) that attach to the bacterial cell membrane. This allows them to inject their genetic material into the bacterial cell, ultimately leading to the lysis (bursting) of the bacterium and the release of new phage particles.","reference":"Kasman LM, Porter LD. Bacteriophages. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed June 18, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK493185/","responses":[{"text":"Complex","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyhedral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spherical","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helical","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16117,"text":"Tumor cells have several different mechanisms. These cells are mainly targeted by the T cells of the body. What is the function of the T cells?","explanation":"**Cytotoxic T cells** release **perforin** molecules, which form pores or channels in the membranes of target cells, including tumor cells. These pores allow the entry of toxic enzymes like granzymes into the target cells, leading to their destruction. This process is a key mechanism by which T cells kill cancer cells.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nT cells do not primarily inhibit the humoral immune response; instead, they regulate and interact with the humoral immune system, but their primary role is in cell-mediated immunity.\r\n\r\nB cells are the primary cells responsible for producing antibodies in the humoral immune response.\r\n\r\nPhagocytosis, the process of engulfing and digesting particles, is primarily carried out by phagocytic cells like macrophages and neutrophils.\r\n\r\nT cells do secrete cytokines that help regulate the immune response, cytokines are typically protein molcules rather than lipids.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2020: 528.","responses":[{"text":"Phagocytose the cancer cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secrete lipid that stimulate growth and activation of both B and T cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibit the humoral immune response","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secrete perforins that create pores in the membrane of target cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Activate humoral immunity against cancer cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16118,"text":"A 25-year-old woman has had several severe episodes of pneumonia in the past 5 months. She has not had frequent or unusual infections before the onset of this pneumonia. Which of the following is the most likely immunodeficiency that predisposes her to these infections?","explanation":"**Recurrent severe infections**, particularly of the respiratory tract like pneumonia, often suggest an issue with antibody-mediated immunity. Antibodies, or **immunoglobulins**, are critical in the body's defense against extracellular pathogens, including many bacteria that cause pneumonia. A **reduced** level of immunoglobulins (hypogammaglobulinemia) can lead to an increased susceptibility to such infections.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nComplement deficiencies more commonly lead to recurrent infections with *Neisseria* species and do not exclusively predispose to pneumonia.\r\n\r\nWhile cytotoxic T cells are crucial for killing virus-infected cells and some types of tumor cells, their dysfunction is more typically associated with viral infections.\r\n\r\nDefect in B cells function could also be a possible cause, as B cells are responsible for producing antibodies. However, the more direct cause related to recurrent pneumonia would be the resultant reduction in immunoglobulin levels rather than the B cell defect per se.\r\n\r\nDefects in MHC I typically present with issues related to viral infections and tumor surveillance, not recurrent pneumonia.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2020: 593.","responses":[{"text":"Mutation in the gene that encodes the C3a portion of the complement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Defect in B cells function","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mutation in one of the gene that encode the class Ⅰ MHC proteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Defect in cytotoxic T cells function","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced level of immunoglobulins","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16119,"text":"A 7-year-old boy presented in the outpatient department with complaints of malaise and lethargy for the last 10 days. He had become inattentive at school, anorexic, and lost 4 kg weight in the last 2 years. On examination, he was thin, anxious, and clinically anemic and also has moderate hepatosplenomegaly. The physician was suspecting a malignant etiology for all these complaints. Which cells are predominantly mediated in antitumor activity?","explanation":"**CD 8 T lymphocytes** play a crucial role in the body's immune response against cancer. They are specifically responsible for recognizing and destroying **tumor cells**. When these cells encounter cancerous cells, they release cytotoxic substances that can lead to the **death** of the tumor cells.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nNeutrophils are white blood cells that primarily play a role in the body's defense against bacterial infections.\r\n\r\nB lymphocytes are involved in antibody production and humoral immunity. While antibodies can have a role in cancer therapy, they are not the primary cells responsible for antitumor activity.\r\n\r\nDendritic cells are antigen-presenting cells that help initiate and modulate immune responses. They are important in the immune system's recognition of pathogens and activation of other immune cells.\r\n\r\nCD 4 T lymphocytes, also known as helper T cells, play a central role in coordinating various immune responses, including those against infections.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2020: 528, 529.","responses":[{"text":"CD 8 T lymphocytes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"CD 4 T lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dendritic cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16120,"text":"A 3rd-year medical student attends a night-long educational retreat and develops a cough and fever. Several different attendees are sick with similar symptoms. Public health officials studying the outbreak suspect contaminated air-conditioning. What could be the cause?","explanation":"***Legionella pneumophila*** is a bacterium responsible for causing a type of pneumonia known as Legionnaires disease. This bacterium thrives in water systems, particularly in warm, stagnant water. When contaminated water is aerosolized and released into the air through **air-conditioning** systems or other sources, people can inhale the bacteria, leading to respiratory symptoms like cough and fever.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n*Proteus mirabilis* is a common cause of urinary tract infections but is not associated with respiratory symptoms or outbreaks due to contaminated air-conditioning.\r\n\r\n*Escherichia coli* is a bacterium commonly found in the gastrointestinal tract and is associated with foodborne illnesses and urinary tract infections, not respiratory outbreaks.\r\n\r\n*Klebsiella pneumoniae* can cause respiratory infections, but it is not typically associated with outbreaks due to contaminated air-conditioning.\r\n\r\n*Neisseria meningitidis* can cause meningitis and sepsis but is not commonly associated with respiratory outbreaks due to contaminated air-conditioning.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2020: 170.","responses":[{"text":"Proteus mirabilis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Legionella pneumophila","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Escherichia coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Klebsiella pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria meningitidis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16129,"text":"A 79-year-old man with end-stage Alzheimer's disease and dysphagia is taking multiple medications. Physical examination reveals xerostomia and a limited gag reflex. Which of the following routes of medication administration would provide the lowest serum drug concentrations?","explanation":"Enteral administration, which involves administering the drug through the gastrointestinal (GI) tract (usually orally), is likely to result in the lowest serum drug concentrations in this patient for several reasons. Difficulty swallowing (dysphagia) in this patient can impair the absorption of medications taken orally while dry mouth (xerostomia) can further complicate oral intake and potentially affect the dissolution and absorption of orally administered drugs.\r\n\r\nMoreover, drugs administered enterally are subject to first-pass metabolism in the liver, which can significantly reduce the amount of active drug reaching the systemic circulation.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nIntrathecal administration (into the spinal canal) directly introduces the drug into the cerebrospinal fluid, bypassing systemic circulation initially, leading to high local concentrations but not necessarily high serum concentrations.\r\n\r\nIntramuscular administration allows the drug to be absorbed directly into the bloodstream from the muscle tissue, providing higher bioavailability than enteral routes.\r\n\r\nTransdermal administration, through the skin, usually ensures consistent and continuous absorption into the bloodstream, bypassing the GI tract and liver metabolism.\r\n\r\nIntravenous administration provides the highest serum drug concentrations as it introduces the drug directly into the bloodstream, ensuring 100% bioavailability.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2021: 6.","responses":[{"text":"Intramuscular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravenous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enteral","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intrathecal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transdermal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16132,"text":"A 28-year-old man with seborrheic dermatitis is prescribed a topical corticosteroid cream by his dermatologist in hopes of alleviating the chronic rash and erythema on the cheeks. Which of the following steps is most critical to achieving a therapeutic drug concentration in plasma?","explanation":"**Absorption** is the process by which the drug molecules pass through any barrier such as the skin or gastrointestinal lining to enter the bloodstream. Once in the bloodstream, the drug can then be distributed to the target tissues, including the skin, where it exerts its therapeutic effect.\r\n\r\nTopical corticosteroid creams need to be absorbed through the skin into the systemic circulation to achieve a therapeutic concentration in the plasma.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nGlycosylation is a process involving the addition of sugar molecules to a drug or protein.\r\n\r\nElimination refers to the removal of a drug from the body, usually after it has exerted its therapeutic effect. It is the opposite of absorption.\r\n\r\nMetabolism involves the chemical alteration of a drug in the body. While metabolism can affect the duration of drug action and the formation of active or inactive metabolites, it is not the critical step for achieving therapeutic drug concentrations in plasma.\r\n\r\nDistribution is the process by which a drug is carried throughout the body via the bloodstream to reach various tissues.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 1.","responses":[{"text":"Metabolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elimination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Absorption","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Distribution","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycosylation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16133,"text":"What is the advantage of a drug administered subcutaneously?","explanation":"**Subcutaneous administration** of a drug allows for the slow and sustained release of the medication into the bloodstream. This results in a more **prolonged duration of action** compared to drugs administered by other routes, such as intravenous or intramuscular injection. Subcutaneous injections are often used for medications that need to provide a continuous or extended therapeutic effect over an extended period.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nSubcutaneous administration does not typically provide immediate drug action, as the absorption rate is slower compared to intravenous administration.\r\n\r\nSubcutaneous administration is not the preferred route for rapidly restoring circulation and blood pressure, which often requires intravenous administration.\r\n\r\nSubcutaneous administration is not typically used for drugs intended for short-term effects.\r\n\r\nIntravenous or intramuscular routes are generally more suitable for rapidly achieving high drug concentrations in the bloodstream.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 3.","responses":[{"text":"Gives immediate drug action","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Can be given when patient is in shock","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fast releasing drugs are given","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"For long duration of action","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"For short duration of action","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16135,"text":"What happens to a drug after the addition of glucuronic acid to it?","explanation":"When **glucuronic acid** is added to a drug, it usually results in the drug's **inactivation**. This process is part of phase II drug metabolism, often referred to as conjugation reactions. The conjugation with glucuronic acid increases the water solubility of the drug, facilitating its excretion in urine. This process is crucial in the detoxification and clearance of many drugs and endogenous substances.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe addition of glucuronic acid increases the water solubility of the drug, making it easier for the body to excrete it.\r\n\r\nGlucuronidation is a phase II reaction, which typically follows phase I reactions (oxidation, reduction, or hydrolysis) but can also occur directly on the parent drug.\r\n\r\nIn newborns, the glucuronidation process is not fully developed. Therefore, they have a reduced capacity to metabolize drugs through this pathway compared to adults.\r\n\r\nCytochrome P450 enzymes are primarily involved in phase I drug metabolism reactions. Phase II reactions like glucuronidation are carried out by different enzymes, such as UDP-glucuronosyltransferase.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 14.","responses":[{"text":"Occurs at the same rate in adults and newborns","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Involves cytochrome P450","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decrease in its water solubility","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leads to inactivation of the drug","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Its an example of phase I reaction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16136,"text":"Which of the following is the most important action of drug metabolism?","explanation":"Drug **metabolism** primarily serves to terminate the action of drugs by converting them into more hydrophilic (water-soluble) substances that can be easily excreted from the body. This process, often occurring in the liver, involves biochemical modifications that typically **reduce the drug's activity** and facilitate its elimination.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nIncreasing drug availability at receptor sites is not the primary role of drug metabolism. While metabolism can sometimes activate prodrugs (inactive compounds that become active only after metabolism), the primary purpose of metabolism is to reduce drug activity and promote excretion.\r\n\r\nDrug tolerance is a phenomenon where repeated use of a drug leads to a diminished effect and is not directly a function of drug metabolism. Tolerance can be influenced by various factors, including changes in receptor sensitivity or drug metabolism, but it is not the primary role of metabolism itself.\r\n\r\nBioavailability refers to the proportion of a drug that enters circulation when introduced into the body and can have an active effect. While metabolism can affect bioavailability, its primary role is to detoxify and prepare the drug for excretion.\r\n\r\nPlasma protein binding involves the reversible interaction of drugs with plasma proteins such as albumin. This binding can influence the drug's distribution, but it is not a direct result of drug metabolism.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2021: 35.","responses":[{"text":"To terminate drug action","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase drug availability at receptor site","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase binding of drug to plasma protein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Affect drugs bioavailability","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Drug tolerance","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16137,"text":"Which organ is responsible for the majority of drug excretion?","explanation":"The majority of **drug excretion** in the body is primarily carried out by the **kidneys**. They play a central role in filtering and eliminating drugs and their metabolites from the bloodstream into the urine. This process is essential for maintaining drug concentration within a therapeutic range.\r\n\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile the lungs play a role in excreting some volatile substances and gases, they are not the primary organ responsible for drug excretion.\r\n\r\nThe liver is involved in drug metabolism (biotransformation), where drugs are often transformed into metabolites that can be more easily excreted. However, the liver is not the primary organ for drug excretion; its main role is in drug metabolism.\r\n\r\nThe skin can excrete certain substances through sweat and sebaceous glands, but it is not a major organ for drug excretion.\r\n\r\nThe gastrointestinal tract can contribute to drug excretion through processes such as drug elimination in feces, but it is not the primary organ responsible for the majority of drug excretion.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 15.","responses":[{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lungs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidney","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrointestinal tract","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16138,"text":"A 16-year-old girl suffering from seasonal rhinitis started therapy with loratadine, a drug that binds H1 histamine receptors. Which of the following terms best defines the intrinsic ability of a drug to bind to a receptor?","explanation":"**Affinity** refers to the degree of attraction or **binding strength** between a drug and its specific receptor. In this case, loratadine is a drug that binds to H1 histamine receptors, indicating a high affinity for those receptors. High affinity means that the drug has a strong tendency to bind to the receptor when it encounters it.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nPotency refers to the concentration or dose of a drug required to produce a specific effect.\r\n\r\nIntrinsic activity, also known as intrinsic efficacy, is a measure of a drug's ability to activate a receptor once it has bound to it. It describes how effectively the drug can elicit a response from the receptor. \r\n\r\nEfficacy refers to the maximal response a drug can produce when it fully activates its receptor. \r\n\r\nReceptor activation simply refers to the process by which a drug or ligand binds to a receptor and triggers a biological response.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2021: 16.","responses":[{"text":"Affinity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Efficacy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Potency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Receptor activation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intrinsic activity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16139,"text":"Why is antagonism between adrenaline and histamine called physiological antagonism?","explanation":"Adrenaline (epinephrine) and histamine exert **opposing effects** in the body. Adrenaline is a hormone and neurotransmitter that stimulates the \"fight or flight\" response, leading to increased heart rate, bronchodilation, and other responses. In contrast, histamine is a compound involved in the body's allergic and inflammatory responses, leading to vasodilation, increased vascular permeability, and bronchoconstriction. These opposing effects make their interaction a form of **physiological antagonism**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe effects of adrenaline and histamine are generally mediated through different receptor systems i.e., adrenergic receptors for adrenaline and histamine receptors for histamine.\r\n\r\nWhile it is true that both adrenaline and histamine are naturally present in the body and affect many physiological processes, the key aspect of physiological antagonism is the opposing physiological effects these substances have on the body.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2021: 20.","responses":[{"text":"Both affect many physiological processes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Both compete with same receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They have opposite physiological effects","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Both are physiologically present in the body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They act on physiological receptors","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16140,"text":"Which receptor type has 7 helical membrane spanning amino acid segments intracellular loops?","explanation":"**G protein-coupled receptors** have seven helical membrane-spanning amino acid segments and intracellular loops. This structural arrangement allows them to interact with intracellular signaling pathways and activate G proteins, which play a crucial role in transmitting signals from extracellular ligands to the cell's interior.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nIntrinsic ion channel-containing receptors form ion channels directly in the membrane.\r\n\r\nTyrosine kinase receptors are characterized by the activation of tyrosine kinase activity upon ligand binding.\r\n\r\nWnt receptors, including Frizzled receptors, are involved in Wnt signaling pathways.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2021: 21.","responses":[{"text":"Intrinsic ion channel containing receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tyrosine protein kinase receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"G protein coupled receptor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gene expression regulating receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Want receptors","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16141,"text":"If a patient comes with a complain of nasal stuffiness, what would be the drug of choice?","explanation":"**Phenylephrine** is a sympathomimetic drug that acts as a **nasal decongestant**. It works by constricting blood vessels in the nasal mucosa, reducing swelling and congestion. This helps to relieve nasal stuffiness and improve breathing.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nPilocarpine is a cholinergic drug used to treat conditions like glaucoma and dry mouth (xerostomia) by increasing salivary gland secretion.\r\n\r\nDopamine is a neurotransmitter and medication used primarily for conditions like shock, low blood pressure, and certain cardiac disorders.\r\n\r\nDobutamine is a medication used to stimulate the heart in cases of heart failure or inotropic support.\r\n\r\nSalmeterol is a long-acting bronchodilator used in the management of asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD).","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 83, 84.","responses":[{"text":"Dobutamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salmeterol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dopamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pilocarpine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phenylepherine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16143,"text":"Which of the following features is not present in an ideal homicidal poison?","explanation":"In an ideal homicidal poison, several characteristics are considered desirable to effectively carry out a poisoning without arousing suspicion. The poison should be easily mixed with food or drink, ensuring that the victim consumes it without suspicion. An ideal homicidal poison should be tasteless and odorless to prevent the victim from detecting any unusual or unpleasant flavors or smells, which could lead to suspicion.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nA rapid-acting poison is preferred to cause quick and lethal effects, minimizing the chances of the victim seeking medical attention or intervention.\r\n\r\nAn ideal homicidal poison should be easy to obtain without arousing suspicion.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Foundation-2 Module, Forensic Medicine slides, Topic: forensic toxicology.","responses":[{"text":"Symptoms should resemble a natural disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Should be palatable","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tasteless and odorless","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Should be rapid in action","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Easily available","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16144,"text":"Some viruses cause the downregulation of major histocompatibility complex (MHC) I complex to evade CD8 cells. Which of the following immune cells are involved in killing such cells with downregulated MHC I?","explanation":"**Natural killer** (NK) cells are a type of innate immune cell that can recognize and kill cells with reduced or missing MHC I expression. NK cells can detect abnormal cells, such as virus-infected cells or cancer cells, by recognizing the **absence of MHC I** molecules. When NK cells identify such target cells, they release cytotoxic molecules, such as perforin and granzymes, which induce cell death in the target cells.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nT cells, including cytotoxic T cells (CD8+ T cells), rely on MHC I molecules to recognize and kill infected or abnormal cells. \r\n\r\nDendritic cells, B cells, and neutrophils play important roles in various aspects of the immune response but are not typically involved in directly killing cells with downregulated MHC I.","reference":"Cornel AM, Mimpen IL, Nierkens S. Mhc class i downregulation in cancer: underlying mechanisms and potential targets for cancer immunotherapy. Cancers. Published July 2, 2020. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32630675/","responses":[{"text":"T cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dendritic cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Natural killer cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

